{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529982"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:01:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:01:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14480"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14480"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.11,0.04,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55731"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41275"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4465"},{"type":"tags","id":"4925"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12185"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"},{"type":"tags","id":"12959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43532"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55731"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her two-week-old infant. She is concerned about her milk supply, reporting that her baby seems hungry all the time and is not gaining weight as expected. This is her first child. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports breastfeeding every three to four hours during the day and once at night. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her breasts are soft and non-tender. The baby appears alert and weight is tracking at the 40th percentile. The woman is keen to continue breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Order serum prolactin levels","Refer for breast ultrasound","Recommend formula supplementation","Prescribe domperidone","Advise increasing breastfeeding frequency"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a common scenario of perceived low milk supply in a first-time mother. The most appropriate first step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadvise increasing breastfeeding frequency\u003C/strong\u003E. Frequent and effective milk removal is the most important factor in stimulating milk production. The current feeding pattern of every three to four hours during the day with only one night feed may not be sufficient to establish and maintain an adequate milk supply, especially in the early weeks postpartum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing domperidone\u003C/strong\u003E, a galactogogue, should not be the first step. Galactogogues should only be considered after addressing modifiable factors affecting milk supply, such as feeding frequency and technique. Moreover, domperidone has potential side effects and should be used judiciously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending formula supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E at this stage may interfere with establishing breastfeeding and could further decrease milk production. It should only be considered if there are clear signs of infant dehydration or failure to thrive, and even then, it should be accompanied by measures to increase breast milk production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering serum prolactin levels\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically necessary in the initial management of perceived low milk supply. Prolactin levels are generally adequate in lactating women, and low levels are rarely the cause of insufficient milk production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for breast ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. While breast ultrasound can be useful in assessing for insufficient glandular tissue in cases of persistent low supply, it is not a first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial approach should focus on optimising breastfeeding management. This includes increasing feeding frequency to at least 8 to 12 times per 24 hours, ensuring proper latch and positioning, and considering breast compression during feeds. If these measures do not improve milk supply and infant weight gain, further evaluation and interventions may be necessary, potentially including lactation consultant referral, assessment for underlying medical conditions, or consideration of galactogogues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Frequent and effective milk removal is the most important factor in increasing milk production.","Galactogogues should only be considered after addressing modifiable factors affecting milk supply, such as feeding frequency and technique.","Low milk supply can be caused by various factors, including insufficient glandular tissue, hormonal imbalances, and ineffective milk removal."],"references":["Kent JC, Ashton E, Hardwick CM, Rea A, Murray K, Geddes DT. Causes of perception of insufficient milk supply in Western Australian mothers. Matern Child Nutr. 2021 Jan;17(1):e13080. doi: 10.1111/mcn.13080. Epub 2020 Sep 20. PMID: 32954674; PMCID: PMC7729526."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41275"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14480"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41275"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T16:59:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T17:00:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7175"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55731"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","